	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>High production potential in East Africa and barriers to intra-regional trade </h1>

			
			<h4>
												13 June 2013
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>A new GRET study of agriculture in the East African Community (EAC) concludes that “the potential for developing regional production is high, especially through increased yields of animal and crop productions.” The study is based primarily on a literature review and supplemented by interviews with the main actors involved with two products that are given special attention: rice and milk.</p><p>By examining closely the supply chain for the two focus products, the study is able to identify (and broadly rank) the constraints to increased production and trade. At the top of the list are poor physical and institutional infrastructure that limit production. It is argued that “to a large extent, the low level of intra-regional trade is more due to the insufficient regional production than to constraints to trade.” </p><p>The study observes that storage infrastructure is poor and transport costs are high (as are those for energy and telecommunications); and poor institutional infrastructure means that the “lack of formal contracts and ability to enforce informal agreements means that most of the deals are done between relatives or close personal friends, which”, the report argues, “increases transaction costs.” </p><p>The study affirms that “the net effect is to tilt bargaining power away from farmers towards intermediaries, reducing the incentive of the former to increase production.” The many formal and informal non-tariff barriers to regional trade exacerbate these underlying difficulties. Because of poor infrastructure surplus, regions often find it physically easier to sell into contiguous areas of neighbours rather than elsewhere in their own country. Infrastructure constraints further undermine net returns to farmers.</p><p>The study considers the absence of incentives particularly severe for the two focus goods, since import prices are much lower than the current cost of domestic production. In the case of rice, for which EAC is in significant deficit, the report cites price differentials in Tanzania showing local rice two-thirds more expensive than imported rice of equivalent quality (see <i>Agritrade</i> article ‘
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/Agriculture/Commodities/Rice/USDA-review-of-policy-constraints-on-competitive-EAC-rice-production" target="_blank">USDA review of policy constraints on competitive EAC rice production</a>’, 9 July 2012). A 75% import tariff is used to bridge this price gap. Similarly, while the region has an overall deficit in milk production, high tariffs are charged on imports in view of the price differentials between local and imported milk products.</p><p>The report concludes that barriers to intra-regional trade should be removed, but that protection from extra-regional imports should be maintained.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>GRET, ‘Intra-regional trade limitations for agricultural commodities in the EAC’, L. Levard and D. Gabagambi, December 2012</p><p>
<a href="http://www.gret.org/publication/intra-regional-trade-limitations-for-agricultural-commodities-in-the-east-african-community-2/" target="_self">http://www.gret.org/publication/intra-regional-trade-limitations-for-agr...</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>The GRET study’s most controversial recommendation– to retain high tariff barriers on imports of rice and milk – is merely asserted and not argued, and it does not include information needed to judge the broad desirability of the proposal. For example, the study does not consider alternative crops that local producers may be better placed to competitively produce, or the relative impact of high tariff protection on total farm output or poor consumers, rather than other policy measures to address underlying production constraints.</p><p>Equally, the study does not explore the use of other trade measures to manage imports in the face of rising consumer demand and efforts to promote local production (similar to those used in the EU rice sector), or the scope for policy initiatives to improve the functioning of local supply chains in ways that enhance production incentives (a growing focus of EU dairy sector policy). There are undoubtedly institutional capacity constraints on the effective management of more sophisticated agricultural trade policies and the design and implementation of policies to strengthen the functioning of supply chains. This is a major constraint across the ACP. This leads to the blunt use of trade instruments such as tariffs, supplemented by a range of special country-based exemptions, which can serve to fuel informal trade.</p><p>The need for more sophisticated policies, however, would appear to be urgent in the dairy sector, where growing regional demand is leading to an increased EU corporate interest in trade and investment in the East African dairy sector (see <i>Agritrade</i> article ‘
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/Agriculture/Commodities/Dairy/End-of-dairy-quotas-leads-to-greater-external-focus-of-EU-dairy-companies" target="_blank">End of dairy quotas leads to greater external focus of EU dairy companies</a>’, 4 March 2013). This could potentially assist in developing local milk production or could further undermine the bargaining power of local milk producers, depending on what form these trade and investment relations take.</p><p>The GRET study is on stronger ground when ranking the constraints to intra-regional trade. It sheds new light on the vexed question of government export bans. These have a limited direct effect on intra-regional trade, since so much of this trade is informal. However, they do serve to undermine returns to farmers. </p><p>Getting to grips with improving the functioning of milk supply chains to improve the negotiating position of milk producers would appear to be a policy issue of growing importance (see <i>Agritrade</i> article ‘
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/Agriculture/Commodities/Dairy/Scope-for-expansion-and-strengthening-of-functioning-of-Kenyan-dairy-sector" target="_blank">Scope for expansion and strengthening of functioning of Kenyan dairy sector</a>’, 31 March 2012).&nbsp;</p>
		</div>
		
		<div class="clear"></div>

		
	</article>

